Introduction
Development economics is an area of study that fundamentally aims to understand
why some countries are rich while others remain poor. Educational attainment has been a
significant topic of debate when it comes to determinants of economic development. Is
educational attainment a result of development or what ignites it? Is it that people who have
an education are able to become more productive economically stimulating economic growth;
or that after a certain amount of economic development people have more access to education
opportunities? Those of the Human Capabilities school of thought believe that education is
essential in the process of economic development. Education is thought to expand the
freedoms of individuals by empowering them with knowledge to become more self-sufficient
in day to day life, as well as being a fundamental human right.
1
This is the most widely
accepted perception of education that has been adopted by significant global development
organizations. It has been incorporated into the United Nations sustainable development
goals particularly in terms of gender equity in education.
2
However, this perspective is more
of a moralistic standpoint versus objectively defining the mechanics of how education affects
economic development. Setting aside the human capabilities approach, this literature review
aims to summarise significant findings in the role of education on economic development
solely from a GDP per capita (or other similar measures) perspective, and draw conclusions
on to what extent it is significant in that regard.
Education Facilitating Economic Development

Some of the earlier economic perspectives on education that defined many of the
policies adopted by economic development organizations were pioneered by Jacob Mincer in
his 1974 paper on human capital analyses on earnings.
3
He quantitatively described the role
of education in the formation of human capital earnings through a mathematical function.
This function relates an individuals earnings to their expected base age of a person with no
experience nor education; the product of the average return on education and average years of
education; the average return to work experience by year of work experience is then
calculated from this function.
4
The results of his work among other academics specializing in
human capital
5
demonstrated how the rate of return of education on income overall tended to
be much higher than other factors. They conclude that with more years of education an
individual should earn more, and in that sense education should raise GPD per capita.
6
The
rationale for this being that with a greater education one is more capable and worth paying
more to do a job than those who have not completed as much education. One real life
example that is considered to demonstrate these results is that of the development of the
Americas. Canada and the United States invested much more into primary and secondary
education than Central American countries did over the past two centuries. It is believed that
because of this Canada and the United States are now much richer than countries in Central
America.
7
Many scholars also attribute the success of the East Asian miracle to significant
investment in education throughout the 1970s and 1980s which was not seen in other
developing countries.

Apart from the argument that education would directly lead to greater productivity
through more capable workers, there are reasons that education would indirectly lead to
economic growth. Education would considerably influence economic development through
its externalities effects. One paper showed through regression analysis that primary and
secondary education tend to have positive health benefits. They particularly seem to increase
with preventative health programs such as immunization and have shown to lower the infant
mortality rate. With a healthier population, there would be a lower mortality rate and higher
productivity in the long run overall since less people getting sick on average.
9
These
externalities also extend to fertility rates. Primary school completion is one of the most
indicative factors that determine total fertility rates across developing countries.
10
Lower
fertility rates have been indicative of economic growth for countries as they transition from
developing to developed.
11
In addition to these examples, it is quite likely many other
externalities of education exist which also promote economic growth.
Some critics have argued although there is substantial evidence for a strong
relationship between education and economic growth the mechanics of this relationship have
not been studied in depth.
12
A more specific study by George Psacharopoulos builds on the
results of Mincer. He found that there are different returns to education depending on the
level of education. It was found that those with a primary or secondary education would
benefit much more from said education that one with a tertiary education in most developing
countries.
13
His research into this subject is what shifted many NGOs to invest more heavily

into primary and secondary education versus tertiary.
14
This shows that although education
has a well-proven positive relationship with income, there are likely more specifics behind
the mechanics of how education affects economic development. The one study mentioned
looked at education levels specifically, but other factors may be the real underlying reasons
for economic growth such as quality of education, education type (vocational versus bachelor
degrees), or gender equity in classrooms.
Criticisms of Education as a Facilitator of Economic Development
Education can explain the differences in income within individual countries, yet this
pattern does not seem to hold across countries. Many countries across the world have similar
levels of educational attainment (e.g. average number of year in school, percentage of
population completing primary, secondary, tertiary education, and other similar measures),
however the GDP per capita of these countries differ greatly.
15
Some also defy the pattern by
having relatively low levels of educational attainment yet high a GPD per capita, and vice
versa, such as Georgia or Kuwait respectively.
16
This is indicative that the relationship
between education and income exists distinctly in individual countries, but doesnt
necessarily translate exactly to all others. Other factors must be working in tandem with
education to alter income. Kuwait and other countries in the Middle East tend to have low
levels of educational attainment yet high GDP per capita. This is due to the success of the oil
industry creating ultra-wealthy elites which drives GDP per capita up without there being
incentive for investment into education for all of its citizens.
17
Countries that were once under
Soviet rule or influence, like Georgia, share its culture of education for all stemming from its
Socialist roots, while also experiencing the lack of GDP growth from the inefficient

5
economies also characterized by Soviet economic policies.
18
These different contexts provide
evidence that education may be a by-product of a developed environment rather than being
the driving factor for development. It is also possible that countries may have many reasons
apart from education that would also explain income e.g. politics, economic policy, culture,
history etc. With so many factors working at the same time as education, it is difficult to tell
if education is the key factor truly driving economic development or also something that
changes from being subject to another driving force.
Another issue is that for many low income countries one of the greatest hurdles is
tackling unemployment. Some critics of investment into education in development countries
point out that there is little point to investing so much into higher education if there is no
market for highly educated employees. Many youths with either a secondary or tertiary
education in developing countries experience employment despite the relationship between
income and educational attainment.
19
The lack of opportunity has been argued to lead to
Brain Drain. This is the process of a countrys highly skilled and educated labourers,
typically those with a tertiary education, leaving the country in order to find work and better
opportunities abroad. It has been argued that Brain Drain has led to a loss of human capital
in developing countries, which has significantly hindered economic growth.
20
However, some
argue that the effects of the Brain Drain phenomena are offset by the volume of remittance
payments which are sent back to the developing country. This has been attributed to the fact
that those with tertiary degrees working abroad tend to earn more, and would also be in a
good position to be able to open a bank account to transfer money across borders. They
would also be inclined to do so for many reasons such as having enough savings from higher

paying jobs as consequence of their tertiary degrees, the prestige of working abroad and
being able to provide for family back home, and in some cases having dependents to support.
Remittance payments then could possibly increase economic growth in these developing
countries more so than the Brain Drain hinders.
21
Conclusion
Like most economic development issues, the relationship between education and
economic growth is multifaceted and complex. There are convincing arguments for both
sides as to whether educational attainment is a key driver of economic development or not. It
seems that education can explain differences in income within individual countries, but once
looked at globally, different countries seem to have different results for similar educational
levels due to other factors. It would appear that education like many other factors does have
its role, but definitely cannot be the sole attributor to economic development overall and
likely is working alongside other mechanisms. The meaning of educational attainment can
also be broken down in terms of specifics on quality and quantity which may yield more
accurate results than the general measures found in most literature. It could be that the true
role of education lies in one of these specific areas that may reveal itself one day with further
research.
